This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with video understanding and action detection. The use of deep learning models and neural networks also suggests that it could belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper's focus on temporal action detection and the use of anchor-free methods could also place it in the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Additionally, the paper's use of dynamic receptive fields and direct prediction of categories and boundaries could suggest it belongs to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper's focus on precise action detection could also place it in the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category.
